growth of the city; how to create demand for goods and services; how to finance transportation improvements such as streets, bridges, roads, and railways; and how to assimilate substantial social and political change. Weaving a strong cast of determined Albertans together with a study of the climate that supported growth and change, Klassen discusses the successes and failures of businesses in this region. Ultimately, it is about how a few people - Isaac G. Baker, Agnes K. Bedingfeld, and James A. Lougheed - helped to create the conditions in which Calgary emerged as a city and the Bow Valley an important agricultural centre.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBusiness enterpriseszAlbertazBow River RegionxHistoryy19th century. 0aBusiness enterpriseszAlbertazCalgaryxHistoryy19th century. 0aBusinesspeoplezAlbertazBow River RegionvBiography. 0aBusinesspeoplezAlbertazCalgaryvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aalberta business history.  abusiness development.  abusiness history.  abusiness studies.  abusinesspeople.  aearly Canadian entrepreneurship.  aentrepreneurship.  ahow entrepreneurship has contributed to the growth of Canada.  apioneer business.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781552383353?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781552383353423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781552383353/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles